{"key":"post-11701296","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11701296</id>\n<content>All bulk substrates including coir should be pasteurized.&amp;nbsp; There's more to pasteurization than just killing mold spores.&amp;nbsp; By 'cooking', we release more of what the mycelium needs.&amp;nbsp; Performance is almost always better on pasteurized bulk substrates than on non-pasteurized.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've often said coir can be used with no heat treatment, but that's more in answer to someone with green mold on their tray.&amp;nbsp; My point is that it's the spawn which was contaminated, not the coir.&amp;nbsp; You'll find performance is better if you'll pasteurize the coir.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11701411</next>\n<prev>11701032</prev>\n<first>11676286</first>\n<last>11726856</last>\n<when>1261531218</when>\n<utime>12/23/09 03:20 AM</utime>\n</post>"}